postcontent:
Arms-list image restrictions forced me to host the photos off site. Please, take a look.

http://i1102.photobucket.com/albums/g459/TravisDatGuyRich/DSC01634_zpsa5795779.jpg

http://i1102.photobucket.com/albums/g459/TravisDatGuyRich/DSC01635_zpsa485d028.jpg

http://i1102.photobucket.com/albums/g459/TravisDatGuyRich/DSC01639_zps1761be05.jpg

http://i1102.photobucket.com/albums/g459/TravisDatGuyRich/DSC01645_zpsf658114c.jpg

Up for sale is a 5.45x39 Saiga. I had planned on this being my "go to" rifle for the future and is set up as such. I jut got bit by the .308 bug instead. This rifle has had about 500 rounds of NON corrosive only ran though it.

It has been converted back from sporter to military form. It has a correct Russian 90* gas block and bayonet lug; both of those things are Russian AK74 milspec and most Saiga conversions don't have this. It also has an Echo 93V3/QD sling mount and Polish Beryl milspec railed hand-guard with vertical foregrip. The hand-guard is Polish MilSpec made of high impact polymer with a aluminum heat shield, great for mounting a tac light to your ak without clamping it to the barrel. It also has a Russian chrome lined muzzle brake, not some off center Tapco paper weight. It does not have the muzzle brake pin, but that is a easy to find $5 part available from APEX or KVAR. It also has a Tapco G2 trigger.

It also comes with 9 Milspec mags, 5 Bulgarian steel reinforced Circle 10 black mags, 1 TAN Bulgarian Circle 21 mag, and 3 Polish Tantal mags that were re-coated by the importer. Again, these are NOT American junk mags, these are all top quality MilSpec mags.

Also includes a BCS industries 5 cell Molle chest rig in ATACS FG with upgraded harness. This is a VERY heavy duty chest rig that will take much abuse.

Also included is an ammo can full of BANNED surplus 7N6 5.45x39 Soviet surplus. A little over 1,000 rounds. If I get a serious inquiry I will make a definite count. 

This rifle AND this ammo is BANNED by our........"great leader"....And NO MORE will be imported. I have the original inspection paperwork from the Izhmash factory.

Will take $1,5000 cash, or trade for semi auto .308's (with cash towards me or you, depending on the trade). HK91's, PTR's, M1A's, GOOD FALs's.

title: For Sale:  WWII 1940 Lee-Enfield Mark III Rifle
postcontent:
WWII 1940 Lee-Enfield Military Rifle .303 caliber, Mark III, Serial # 1439XX on both receiver and underside of wood. Crown over “G.R.” = George Rex (George VI, King of England during WWII), manufacture date “1940” + “Sht.L.E” = Short Lee Enfield (short magazine) + star + “III.” =  Mark III, made 1915-1953. Manufacturer’s mark “M” = Maltby, Royal Ordinance Factory in Maltby, Yorkshire, “BSA” under stacked rifles on bolt = Birmingham Small Arms logo, a number of proof marks and inspector’s marks on metal and wood. 

History: At the outbreak of WWII, BSA was the only factory producing rifles in the UK. During the Battle of Britain in 1940 the BSA factory was bombed several times by the Luftwaffe, destroying the machine shops and stopping rifle production.  The British government and BSA immediately established “shadow factories” throughout Britain to increase arms production in areas less vulnerable to German air attacks. The Royal Ordinance Factory was then established at Maltby and produced Enfield rifles. This rifle was one of those produced early in the war during the Battle of Britain.

I bought this as a collectible and have not fired it, but everything functions perfectly. Was used in WWII. Good cond.
$275 local sale

This listing is for One set of grips. Buyers, however, may take any number of extras we have on hand at the same per-set price and with no additional shipping charges. Photos show off white polymer, imitation ivory replacement grips to fit S&W models 469 and 669 pistols chambered in 9mm caliber. Smith & Wesson only produced the 469 and 669 compacts between 1983 and 1988, but they were immensely popular and without peer. These little guns are so durable, they will be in service as long as any of our readers shall live. These are replacement panels, virtually identical to most of the issue grips except without logo. Construction is hard off white or ivory color polymer with standard size reverse detent risers, and with checkered texture lower panels. Since a person has to disassemble the pistol and its grip frame to install them, we advise at least consulting howto com or a credible disassembly video. These grips will only fit Smith & Wesson Model 469 and 669 pistols. They will Not fit a Smith & Wesson model 3913, will Not fit a model 6906, will Not fit a model 59, will Not fit the nozzle of a 1966 Fleet’s brand saline bottle. They will only fit S&W 469 and 669 pistols chambered in 9mm, often known as the Mini. Grips for any discontinued Smith & Wesson pistol are not easy to find, and these are among the most difficult. From our poor memory, no one made imitation ivory grips for the Minis, even when they were in production by S&W. We’re offering them per set at only $ 29.00.

A nice example of the Remington Rolling Block.  In .43 Spanish, it was the chief service arm of the Spanish Army from 1870–1893, and was used by reserve and militia forces for many years thereafter.  The rifle exhibits great case hardening color on the receiver and butt plate with only a small patch of wear at the heal of the butt plate and around the chamber block hinge pin from take down for cleaning.  Bluing on the barrel and other parts in very good condition, especially when you consider that this rifle is at least 120 years old.  Chamber and barrel are clean, not dark and look perfect for shooting.  The original cleaning rod is included; an often lost accessory,  The rifle shows little use.  The stock is very good, with the usual handling marks and evidence of a small arsenal repair at the wrist.  This should be a great shooter and also a beautiful piece for display.  Cases and reloading supplies are easily found for this caliber.  I have tried to describe this beautiful rifle fully but if you have any questions feel free to contact me.
Note that this is a pre 1898 rifle and not subject to FFL transfer.  I will transfer on a copy of your drivers license or similar government ID showing birth date.  At this price free shipping to the lower 48.

Hey all. 

Had a deal on this, but they bailed out after making me drive an hour and wait two. So to try this again....


I picked up this awesome weapon in trade, but because I already have a hand cannon, I am not as in love with it as I thought. It is an awesome piece, and is a first gen Israeli import pistol. The .357 DE can handle the hottest of loads, and runs flawlessly, chewing through everything. The frame size is slightly smaller than the .44 (slightly) which makes it easier and more comfortable to shoot. The bore has polygonal rifling, much like an HK. 


This is a very early serial number, 83xx... First run!


This pistol is a real show stopper, and is in absolutely stunning condition. The BCG is clean, and there is very, very little handling wear. (Most DE pistols are handled more than they are shot.) 

The pistol will include one magazine and a hard case. 

This variant of DE is far more affordable to shoot, as .357 mag ammo is far cheaper than 44 or 50!


I will sell for 900.00

title: For Sale:  S&W #2 Army
location: N. Raleigh, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
Smith and Wesson #2 Army

this is a 32 caliber rim fire, six shot revolver whose barrel swings up to allow the non-fluted cylinder to be removed for loading. It has a 5” octagon barrel and a spur trigger. It is referred to as a model Number 2 old model revolver and also the model number 2 Army. This is because earlier issues of this gun were used extensively as a personal side arm by officers and enlisted men during the Civil War. This gun has a blue finished and shows wear. However, the overall condition is very good and it functions very well. The grips are varnish rosewood with a square butt profile. The grips have an "x" notched into it on one side, possibly a marking from a kill in the war? A total of 77,155 of these were manufactured from 1861 to 1874. As a history note, General George Armstrong Custer was known to own a pair of these and ‘Wild Bill” Hitchcock, while Marshall of deadwood was carrying a model Army number 2 the night he was shot holding aces and eights in August of 1874
